In this example, we can see a basic example of strategy in arranging your atoms to tasks.
- The front and two sides of the molecule are packed with defensive atoms.
The back is left vulnerable. If you want to keep a molecule quick and light, you can
strategically place the armor based on where you think it'll take the most damage.
- The middle front reveals the tip of the iceberg of attacking atoms. In core gameplay,
atoms cannot shoot through one another. Thus, a piece of the 'weapon' must be exposed.
Hiding the rest behind armor is a good strategy to keep it from taking damage in combat.
- The atoms providing thrust are in three groups. The middle one provides the most
centralized thrust, while the outer two allow for mobility and rotation to the molecule.
- There are two power plants, or energy producing groupings of atoms. Each one is adjacent
to all of the other groupings of the molecule.
- Roles are combined in powers of 2. In the 22 advancment model of core, groupings get an
additional boost to effects when they reach 2, 4, 8, 16, 32, 64 and so on atoms.
Arrangements of these sizes are typically the most effective in terms of use of mass, time,
